Q1. What Exactly is a Constructor? 💡
Standard Definition:
    A constructor is a special method in Java that is automatically called when an object is created. Its job is to initialize the object’s values.

# Fundamental Concepts of Constructors 🔑
    Here are some important points to remember:
        1. The constructor name must be the same as the class name
        2. It has no return type (not even void)
        3. It is called automatically when an object is created
        4. You can have multiple constructors in one class — this is called constructor overloading
        5. There are two main types:
            i. Default constructor — no parameters also know as ZERO Parameterized Constructor, Java Complier will create the Default Constructor if you don't create the constructor
           ii. Parameterized constructor — takes input values
# Common Interview Questions & Answers 💬
    Q1. What is a constructor in Java?
        A constructor is a special method used to initialize objects. It runs automatically when an object is created.

    Q2. What’s the difference between a constructor and a method?
        1. A constructor has no return type
        2. A constructor’s name is always the same as the class name
        3. It runs automatically; you don’t call it like a method

    Q3. What is a default constructor?
        A constructor with no parameters. It sets default values.

    Q4. What is a parameterized constructor?
        A constructor that takes values (parameters) and uses them to set data during object creation.